##### Layer 6 Presentation ######





•••••presentation..


The Presentation Layer (Layer 6) is responsible for translating, encrypting/decrypting, and compressing data. It ensures that data sent by one device can be understood by another, even if they use different data formats.
Think of it as a translator between the Application Layer and the lower network layers.


Main Functions
1. Data Translation
Different systems may represent data differently. The Presentation Layer converts data into a common format.
Example:
Windows sends text in one encoding.
Linux or macOS receives it.
The Presentation Layer ensures the text is displayed correctly.
2. Encryption
It encrypts data before transmission so that unauthorized people cannot read it.
Example: When you log in to your bank's website using HTTPS, your password is encrypted before being sent.
Common technologies:
SSL
TLS

3. Decryption
On the receiving side, the encrypted data is decrypted back into its original form.
Example:
Sender:
Password → Encrypt → Send

Receiver:
Receive → Decrypt → Password
4. Data Compression
It reduces the size of data before sending it to save bandwidth and speed up transmission.
Example:
Compressing an image before sending it over the internet.
Compressing a video during streaming.

Real-Life Example
Imagine you're sending a photo on WhatsApp:
Application Layer (Layer 7): You tap Send.
Presentation Layer (Layer 6):
Compresses the image.
Encrypts it.
Converts it into a format the receiver can understand.
Lower layers send the data across the network.
On the receiver's phone, Layer 6:
Decrypts the data.
Decompresses the image.
Converts it back into a displayable format.
Common Data Formats Handled
JPEG
PNG
GIF
MP3
MP4
ASCII
Unicode
JSON
XML
Easy Analogy
Imagine you and your friend speak different languages.
You speak English.
Your friend speaks French.
A translator converts your English into French before sending the message and translates it back on the other side.
The Presentation Layer acts like that translator.


